# Purpose: Teach Claude how to produce *good-looking* geometry per piece,
# given that piece's local context. The craft guide for the toddler-with-blocks
# approach.
#
# This document should cover:
#
# 1. Reading a context packet
#    - What to notice in the neighbor list
#    - How "edge" vs "interior" should change the geometry
#    - What "facing" information means for orientation
#
# 2. Primitive vocabulary and composition patterns
#    - Cross-reference threejs-conventions.md
#    - Common block arrangements: tree (trunk + foliage), chair (seat + back + legs),
#      wall segment, fence post, etc. TEACHING examples, not templates.
#    - Footprint discipline: your primitives must fit within the piece's cell size
#
# 3. Contextual variation — the actual craft
#    - "Tree near path" vs "tree deep in forest" — what changes
#    - "Chair at head of table" vs "chair on side" — what changes
#    - "Wall corner" vs "wall middle" — what changes
#    - Pattern: observe context, pick ONE thing to vary, make the small choice
#
# 4. Anti-patterns to avoid
#    - Reusing exact primitive sequences across pieces
#    - Ignoring the context packet ("just make a tree")
#    - Over-varying (each piece wildly different — becomes noise)
#    - Under-varying (minor rotation tweaks only — stamping in disguise)
#
# 5. When fallback is appropriate
#    - Claude can't meaningfully vary every piece on every scene
#    - Which kinds of pieces benefit most from per-piece authoring (trees,
#      props, anything with visible individuality) vs which don't (tiled
#      floor cells, identical paving stones — here reuse is okay)
